Plants in W ater
Plan ts that are found in water are called aqua tic plan ts. On the basis of how they 
grow, they are divided into three groups.
1. Free-floating plan ts– Plan ts like duckw eed, water hyacinth, water lettuce, 
water ches tnut etc. that float on the surface of water are called free floating 
plan ts. The roots of these plan ts are poorly developed or even absent. The 
body of these plan ts is light and spongy so that they can float freely on the 
surface of water.
2. Submer ged (Under water) plan ts– Plan ts like hydrilla, tape grass, pondw eed 
etc. remain comple tely immer sed in water. The roots of these plan ts are fixed 
to the w aterbed. The lea ves of these plan ts ar e narr ow with no por es. The y

3. Fixed-floating plan ts– Floating plan ts whose roots are fixed to the waterbed 
are called 'Fixed-floating plan ts' e.g. lotus, water lily etc. Such plan ts have 
long hollo w stems which reach the surface of water and keep the leaves and 
flowers afloat. Their leaves are waxy and have stoma ta on the upper side.
Animals in W ater
Animals that live in or on the surface of water are called aqua tic animals. Water is 
home t o a hug e variety of aqua tic animals such as dif ferent species of fish, w ater 
mammals, shelled animals, water birds, insects etc.
Fish– Fish have a streamlined body and fins that help them swim in water. They 
breathe through gills. Goldfish, catfish, carp, trout, seahor se etc. are different 
types of fish found in water.
Environmental Studies-551

Water mammals–  Dolphins and whales are mammals that live in water. They give 
birth to young ones and breathe with lungs. They keep coming to the surface of 
water to breathe in fr esh air . The y also ha ve fins and s treamlined bodies lik e fish, 
which help them swim.
Water birds– Water birds such 
as ducks or heron breathe 
through lungs and tiny nostrils 
located at the top of their 
beaks. Ducks have webbed 
feet which help them to swim 
while herons have long and slim legs that help them to stand in water.
Amphibians– Amphibians are 
animals like toads and frogs 
that can live both on land and 
in water. When they are in 
water, they breathe through 
their mois t skin and when on 
land, they use their lungs for breathing. They lay eggs in water and the young ones 
live and grow in water till they become adult.
Mosquit oes– Mosquit oes do not live in water but they lay eggs in stagnan t water. A 
mosquit o is a parasitic insect that feeds on animals and human blood. Mosquit oes 
spread man y dang erous diseases like malaria, dengue, chick engunia etc. 
Shelled animals– Turtles, 
crabs, snails, prawns and 
lobsters are also aquatic 
animals. They have a hard 
protective shell as an outer 
covering. These animals have 
paddle-lik e flipper s and special limb s that help them to walk across the bottom of 
the water bodies. They breathe through gills.

Prevention– It is import ant to prevent the outbr eak of malaria and dengue. Some 
tips on how this can be done are–
! Do not let water collect in or around your house.
! Chang e the water in water cooler s every 2-3 days. 
! Clean water pots and tanks regularly .
! Use mosquit o nets, coils, mats etc. at nigh t.
! Spray kerosene oil on stagnan t water.
! Keep your surroundings clean.
! Spray DDT around the area wher e mosquit oes could breed.
! Wear clothes that cover your arms and legs.
Environmental Studies-553Symptoms of Malaria and Dengue
Malaria– Chills, fever and sweating. Nausea and headache also occur with fever.
Dengue – High fever, severe headache, muscles and joint pains, vomiting , eye pain 
and rashes.

How Does Food Get Spoilt
Some very tiny living beings called micr o-or ganism or micr obes are always presen t 
in our environmen t. Micr obes are so small that they can not be seen with our 
naked eyes. They can be seen only through micr oscope. Food is very import ant for our survival. Some food items like fruits, bread, 
vegetables, etc. get spoiled in a short span of time if not kept in the 
refrigerator. Such food items are called perishable foods. Wher eas foods like 
pulses, grains, sugar, hone y etc. can be used over a long time and do not 
requir e refrigeration. They are called non perishable or imperishable foods.From the pictur es given below , tick (3) the foods that can be used for a 
long time and do not requir e refrigeration.

These micr obes grow rapidly in warm air and 
humid conditions. If the cooked food, milk and 
other perishable foods are left lying around for a 
long time, micr obes begin to grow on or in the 
food, leading to the spoiling of food. Spoiled 
food may have a foul smell, chang e in colour , 
sticky feel and a sour taste. Eating spoiled food 
can mak e us sick. It can also lead to a serious 
condition called food poisoning which often 
includes upset stomach, diarrhoea and vomiting.

Preventing Spoilage
We can follow a few simple practices to prevent spoilag e of food.
! Perishable foods like milk, fruits and vegetables mus t be kept in the fridg e.
! Food should preferably be prepared fresh, in required quantity and 
consumed as soon as possible.
! Foods like spices, cereals, biscuits and other snack s should be kept in air tight 
container s.
! Shelv es and cupboar ds mus t be kept clean and dry. This will prevent spoilag e 
of stored food by insects ,worms and rats.
Environmental Studies-557

Preservation of Food
It is not always possible to eat all the food that we have bough t or cooked. So, we 
need to preser ve food. Food preser vation is the process of treating and handling 
food to stop spoilag e by micr obes ( bact eria and fungi).Some methods of food 
preser vation are–
1. Freezing– Bact eria and fungi can not survive in low temper ature. 
So, some foods are frozen to prevent them from spoilag e. Cook ed 
and raw food items are stored in the refrigerator at home. Cold 
stores are used to preser ve large amoun t of food stuff for a long er 
period of time.
2. Cooking–  Heating and boiling food kills bact eria and fungi and prevent the food 
from spoiling. Milk is boiled to prevent it from getting spoilt.
3. Sunning and Drying–  The water in the food 
item dries up if it is kept in the sun. Bact eria 
and fungi cannot live without water. Pulses 
can be preser ved by drying them in the heat 
of the sun.
4. Pickling–  Pickling is one of the traditional 
methods of preser ving foods like mang oes, 
lemon ,carrots, raddish and other vegetables. 
In this method, the ingredien ts are dried and 
then oil ,salt and preser vatives are added to it.
5. Canning and Bottling–  The traditional methods 
of sun drying and pickling have chang ed with 
time. Now, the food stuffs are cooked and stored 
in steriliz ed tin container s. Fruits and vegetables 
are canned so that no air can enter and hence 
germs do not grow. Food sealed in tins, bottles, 
Environmental Studies-5 58

etc. can be kept at room temper ature as long as they are not opened. Once they 
are opened, they should be eaten quickly or put in a refrigerator.
6. Adding preser vatives– Biscuits and sweets gener ally contain added chemic als 
called preser vatives so that they do not get spoilt. Salt, sugar, vineg ar and 
certain chemicals like sodium benzoate and sodium metabisulphite are 
commonly used preser vatives.
7. Packaging–  Some food items such as juices are stored 
in especially made pack s called tetra pack s. Food is 
packed in tetra packs using nitrogen gas or by 
remo ving air.
8. Pasteurisation– Milk is preserved by the 
process of pasteurisa tion. In this process, the 
milk is heated to a set temper ature for a short 
period and then suddenly cooled to a very low 
temper ature to kill the germs in it. Pasteuriz ed 
milk can be used for a few days as it does not get 
spoilt quickly .
Scarcity of Food
Ther e are times when availability of food is scarce. The causes of food short age 
may be natural or man-made. The natural causes of food scarcity may be drough ts, 
floods or diseases to the crops.
The man made causes of food scarcity are : black - mark eting and illegal hoar ding . 
At times when there is a short age of food supply , some shopk eeper s hold food 
items and later sell them at higher prices.
Famine in Bengal
When there is a severe short age of food, it is called a famine. The Beng al famine of 
1943 occur ed during World War II. It took place because the British burn t the rice 
fields in Beng al. About three million people died of starvation and malnutrition in 
Beng al due to this famine. 
Environmental Studies-559

Food For All
Millions of people starve everyday because they do not get anything to eat. So, we 
should try not to waste any food. To stop the wastage, we should take following 
steps–
! Do not buy and cook food in excess.
! Do not leave food in plate, take according to your appe tite.
! Store and preser ve the food properly .
! If the food is left over, shar e it with the poor and needy people.

ŸPerishable food should be kept in the refrigerator and rest in air tight container s.
ŸFreezing, drying, canning , boiling , pickling , etc are some methods of food 
preser vation.
ŸPasteuriz ation is a special technique to preser ve milk. 
ŸEverybody needs food to survive so it should not be wasted.
